---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Platform | BeaconGuard Runtime Control Capabilities"
  description="BeaconGuard provides a Control Plane, Compliance Playbooks, Active Verified Releases, a Runtime Control Boundary, and Verifiable Decision Records for high-risk enterprise workflows."
>
  <section class="stack-section">
    <h1>Platform capabilities for deterministic runtime control</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      BeaconGuard separates governed release management from runtime enforcement. Compliance Playbooks become Active Verified Releases; the Runtime Control Boundary evaluates trusted request context and returns explicit ALLOW or DENY results before governed execution.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>Existing systems remain in place</h2>
    <p>
      BeaconGuard does not replace the system of record, workflow application, case-management platform, EHR, AML system, fraud system, SIEM, IAM, or GRC tool. Those systems continue to own their existing functions. BeaconGuard enforces the request boundary before governed AI, APIs, or automated systems execute and emits a Verifiable Decision Record for every deterministic result.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>BeaconGuard Control Plane</h2>
    <p>
      The management plane defines, validates, compiles, approves, signs, and distributes immutable release artifacts. A distributed release is not automatically active. It must pass Release Verification and Activation before it becomes the Active Verified Release used by the runtime.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>Compliance Playbooks</h2>
    <p>
      Compliance Playbooks express governed control intent for regulated workflows. They are the source definition for what must be validated before governed execution proceeds.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>Validation and Compilation</h2>
    <p>
      Playbooks are validated and compiled into a deterministic form suitable for release packaging. Compilation does not replace governance approval or release signing.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>Signed Immutable Release Artifact</h2>
    <p>
      Approved playbooks become Signed Immutable Release Artifacts for controlled distribution. Release identity travels with the package used at runtime.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>Release Verification and Activation</h2>
    <p>
      Distributed releases are verified and activated before they govern evaluation. Only an Active Verified Release is used by the Runtime Control Boundary.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>BeaconGuard Runtime Control Boundary</h2>
    <p>
      The runtime data plane validates and normalizes request context; performs trust, freshness, and replay checks; evaluates each request against the Active Verified Release; and returns ALLOW or DENY before downstream execution. Admission failures fail closed as DENY.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>System Connector</h2>
    <p>
      An optional System Connector maps source protocols and context into the required request format when enterprise applications do not natively produce that structure. The System Connector does not evaluate controls, activate releases, or bypass fail-closed enforcement.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>Deterministic decision results</h2>
    <div class="section-grid section-grid--compact">
      <div class="content-card">
        <h3>ALLOW</h3>
        <p>The request satisfies Active Verified Release requirements and may proceed to governed execution.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="content-card">
        <h3>DENY</h3>
        <p>The request is blocked before downstream execution. Missing approvals or trust conditions produce DENY with an explicit deterministic reason. An illustrative reason style is <code>APPROVAL_REQUIRED</code>.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>
      Human or governance review may follow from the Verifiable Decision Record or an associated obligation. Review does not permit execution and does not replace the ALLOW or DENY result.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>Verifiable Decision Records</h2>
    <p>
      Every deterministic result emits a Verifiable Decision Record that preserves decision context, release identity, control result, and outcome for reconstruction, replay support, audit, and governance review.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>Evidence, Replay, and Verification</h2>
    <p>
      Evidence is designed for replay and verification. Retention, integrity protection, and storage durability depend on the configured evidence provider and customer deployment. Do not treat evidence claims as legal certification or universal append-only storage.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>Industry capability surfaces</h2>
    <div class="section-grid section-grid--compact">
      <div class="content-card">
        <h3>Healthcare</h3>
        <p>Approved pathways, role and trust checks, and Verifiable Decision Records for PHI-sensitive operational workflows.</p>
        <p><a href="/healthcare">Review Healthcare</a></p>
      </div>
      <div class="content-card">
        <h3>Financial</h3>
        <p>Deterministic request admission for AML, KYC, fraud, dispute, and customer-impacting recommendation workflows.</p>
        <p><a href="/fintech">Review Financial</a></p>
      </div>
      <div class="content-card">
        <h3>Regulated automation</h3>
        <p>Fail-closed enforcement before agents or automations act against production systems.</p>
        <p><a href="/canonical-workflow">Review Workflow Examples</a></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="stack-section">
    <h2>Deep technical paths</h2>
    <div class="page-actions">
      <a class="btn-primary" href="/how-it-works">See How It Works</a>
      <a class="btn-secondary" href="/docs/architecture">System Architecture</a>
      <a class="btn-secondary" href="/docs/enforcement-runtime">Enforcement Runtime</a>
      <a class="btn-secondary" href="/healthcare">Healthcare path</a>
      <a class="btn-secondary" href="/fintech">Financial path</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
